                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d436">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">868.51 War Credits/659: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in Great Britain</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Bingham</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">London</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1934-03-24T13:00:00+00:00"
                            >March 24, 1934—1 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/>[Received March 24—9:55 a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>130. Foreign Office states informally that it had received word through the
                    I.F.C. of the Greek Government’s decision outlined in the first paragraph of the
                    Embassy’s 102, March 7, 1 p.m., but that no official reply had yet been made
                    pending the result of semiofficial negotiations now progressing to clarify the
                    French position. It stated further that its official reply, when made, would
                    stipulate that the American loan be included in any arrangement for partial
                    service payment on foreign debt.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Bingham</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
